value.value: A chromosome localization process whereby chromosomes are positioned in a specific order and orientation at the metaphase plate (spindle equator), during meiosis II chromosome segregation. This alignment ensures that each daughter cell will receive the correct number of chromosomes during cell division.

A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of structures in the space external to the outermost structure of a cell. For cells without external protective or external encapsulating structures this refers to space outside of the plasma membrane, and also covers the host cell environment outside an intracellular parasite.

A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of the intracellular bridge. An intracellular bridge is a direct link between the cytoplasms of sister cells that allows cells to communicate with one another.
Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of cell death by apoptotic process.

definition.value: This term should only be used when it is not possible to determine which phase or subtype of the apoptotic process is positively regulated by a gene product. Whenever detailed information is available, the more granular children terms should be used.

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of cell death by apoptotic process.

definition.value: This term should only be used when it is not possible to determine which phase or subtype of the apoptotic process is negatively regulated by a gene product. Whenever detailed information is available, the more granular children terms should be used.

value.value: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of programmed cell death, cell death resulting from activation of endogenous cellular processes.

label.value: positive regulation of programmed cell death

value.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of programmed cell death, cell death resulting from activation of endogenous cellular processes.

label.value: negative regulation of programmed cell death

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of programmed cell death, cell death resulting from activation of endogenous cellular processes.
The nucleus of a germ cell, a reproductive cell in multicellular organisms.
The nucleus of a megasporocyte, a diploid cell that undergoes meiosis to produce four megaspores, and its descendents.
The activation of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of acetate.
Either of two nuclei located centrally in a flowering plant embryo sac that eventually fuse to form the endosperm nucleus.
The nucleus of an antipodal cell, one of three cells of the embryo sac in angiosperms, found at the chalazal end of the embryo away from the point of entry of the pollen tube, and its descendents.
The nucleus of a plant egg cell. This nucleus is found at the micropylar end of the embryo.
The narrow gap that separates the presynaptic and postsynaptic membranes, into which neurotransmitter is released.

The hardening, enlarging and rising of the penis which often occurs in the sexually aroused male and enables sexual intercourse. Achieved by increased inflow of blood into the vessels of erectile tissue, and decreased outflow.
Any process that activates or increases the activity of an enzyme.
Any process that stops or reduces the activity of an enzyme.
Any process that modulates the rate of GTP hydrolysis by a GTPase.
The directed movement of amino acids into a cell or organelle.
A cytokinesis process that involves a set of conserved proteins including FtsZ, and results in the formation of two similarly sized and shaped cells.

definition.value: Note that this term is intended for the annotation of prokaryotic gene products.

value.value: Any process which produces a useful metabolic compound from derivatives of it without de novo synthesis, as carried out by individual cells.

label.value: regulation of GTP cyclohydrolase I activity

value.value: Any process that modulates the activity of the enzyme GTP cyclohydrolase I.
Any process that generates purine nucleobases, one of the two classes of nitrogen-containing ring compounds found in DNA and RNA, from derivatives of them without de novo synthesis.

Any process that generates a pyrimidine nucleoside, one of a family of organic molecules consisting of a pyrimidine base covalently bonded to a sugar ribose, from derivatives of it, without de novo synthesis.
Any process which produces a purine deoxyribonucleoside from derivatives of it, without de novo synthesis.
Any process that generates a pyrimidine deoxyribonucleoside from derivatives of it, without de novo synthesis.
Any process that generates pyrimidine nucleobases, 1,3-diazine organic nitrogenous bases, from derivatives of them without de novo synthesis.
Any process that generates a purine-containing compound, any nucleobase, nucleoside, nucleotide or nucleic acid that contains a purine base, from derivatives of them without de novo synthesis.
Any process which produces an amino acid from derivatives of it, without de novo synthesis.
Any process that generates hypoxanthine, 6-hydroxy purine, from derivatives of it without de novo synthesis.
Any process involved in the controlled movement of a bacterial cell which is dependent on the presence of type IV pili. Includes social gliding motility and twitching motility.
The process of withdrawing a pilus back into a cell.

label.value: rDNA spacer replication fork barrier binding

value.value: Binding to replication fork barriers found in rDNA spacers, sites that inhibit replication forks in the direction opposite to rDNA transcription.

Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of DNA replication by impeding the progress of the DNA replication fork. Replication fork arrest is one of the 'quality control' processes ensuring that DNA-dependent DNA replication occurs correctly. DNA replication fork arrest during DNA-dependent DNA replication is not known to occur outside of cases where a replication error needs to be prevented or corrected.

definition.value: See also the biological process term 'site-specific replication termination ; GO:0071170' and its children.

value.value: The chemical reactions and pathways involving a receptor molecule, a macromolecule that undergoes combination with a hormone, neurotransmitter, drug or intracellular messenger to initiate a change in cell function.
The receptor metabolic process that results in grouping of a set of receptors at a cellular location, often to amplify the sensitivity of a signaling response.
Any process that modulates the extent to which blood vessels can be pervaded by fluid.
Catalysis of the reaction: NAD+ + precorrin-2 = 2 H+ + NADH + sirohydrochlorin.
Any process that reduces the extent to which blood vessels can be pervaded by fluid.
Any process that increases the extent to which blood vessels can be pervaded by fluid.
Binding to tumor necrosis factor, a proinflammatory cytokine produced by monocytes and macrophages.
Binding to a neurotrophin, any of a family of growth factors that prevent apoptosis in neurons and promote nerve growth.

definition.value: Note that mammalian NT-5 was initially named differently from amphibian NT-4 because of sequence differences, but the two genes were later shown to be functionally equivalent [SF:919858].

label.value: regulation of canonical NF-kappaB signal transduction

value.value: Any process that modulates the canonical NF-kappaB signaling cascade.

label.value: positive regulation of canonical NF-kappaB signal transduction

value.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of a canonical NF-kappaB signaling cascade.

label.value: negative regulation of canonical NF-kappaB signal transduction

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of a canonical NF-kappaB signaling cascade.
Binding to the protein-tyrosine kinase receptor ErbB-3/HER3.
Any process involved in the maintenance of a steady-state level of a surface-active agent that maintains the surface tension of a liquid.
Binding to ubiquitin, a protein that when covalently bound to other cellular proteins marks them for proteolytic degradation.
The process in which nucleated precursor cells lose their nucleus during erythrocyte maturation.
